{"title_page": "Cannonball Adderley", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{short description|American jazz alto saxophonist}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Cannonball Adderley\n| image            = Julian and Nat Adderley 1966.JPG\n| caption          = Cannonball (left) with brother [[Nat Adderley]] in 1966\n| background       = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_name       = Julian Edwin Adderley\n| alias            = \n| birth_date       = {{birth date|1928|9|15|mf=y}}\n| birth_place      = [[Tampa]], [[Florida]], U.S.\n| death_date       = {{death date and age|1975|8|8|1928|9|15|mf=y}}\n| death_place      = [[Gary, Indiana]], U.S.\n| instrument       = [[Alto saxophone]], [[soprano saxophone]]\n| genre            = [[Hard bop]], [[soul jazz]], [[modal jazz]], [[Jazz fusion|jazz rock]]<ref>{{cite web |last=Ginell |first=Richard S |url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=black-messiah-mw0000870617|pure_url=yes}} |title=Black Messiah \u2013 Cannonball Adderley : Songs, Reviews, Credits, Awards |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=July 8, 2012}}</ref>\n| occupation       = Teacher, saxophonist\n| years_active     = 1955&ndash;1975\n| label            = [[Blue Note Records|Blue Note]], [[Fantasy Records|Fantasy]], [[Capitol Records|Capitol]], [[Prestige Records|Prestige]], [[Riverside Records|Riverside]]\n| associated_acts  = [[Nat Adderley]], [[Miles Davis]], [[George Duke]], [[Yusef Lateef]], [[Samuel Jones (musician)|Sam Jones]], [[Joe Zawinul]], [[Louis Hayes]], [[Bobby Timmons]], [[Bill Evans]]\n| website          = \n}}\n\n'''Julian Edwin''' \"'''Cannonball'''\" '''Adderley''' (September 15, 1928 \u2013 August 8, 1975) was an American [[jazz]] [[Alto saxophone|alto saxophonist]] of the [[hard bop]] era of the 1950s and 1960s.<ref name=obit/><ref name=\"Harvard Bio\">{{cite book |last=Randel |first=Don Michael |title=The Harvard Biographical Dictionary of Music |year=1996 |publisher=Harvard University Press |location=Cambridge, Massachusetts |isbn=0-674-37299-9 |page=[https://archive.org/details/harvardbiographi00rand/page/5 5] |chapter=Adderley, Cannonball |url=https://archive.org/details/harvardbiographi00rand/page/5 }}</ref><ref name=\"RCJE\">{{Cite book | author = Richard Cook | year = 2005 | title = Richard Cook's Jazz Encyclopedia | publisher = Penguin Books  | isbn = 0-141-00646-3 | page = 3}}</ref>\n\nAdderley is remembered for his 1966  soul jazz single \"[[Mercy, Mercy, Mercy]]\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/song/mercy-mercy-mercy-mt0009193426|title=Mercy, Mercy, Mercy \u2013 Cannonball Adderley \u2013 Song Info \u2013 AllMusic|website=AllMusic|accessdate=August 1, 2018}}</ref> a crossover hit on the pop charts (it was also covered by [[the Buckinghams]]). He worked with trumpeter [[Miles Davis]], on his own 1958 ''[[Somethin' Else (Cannonball Adderley album)|Somethin' Else]]'' album, and on the seminal Davis records ''[[Milestones (Miles Davis album)|Milestones]]'' (1958) and ''[[Kind of Blue]]'' (1959).  He was the elder brother of jazz [[trumpet]]er [[Nat Adderley]], a longtime member of his band.<ref name=\"ALLMUSIC\" />\n\n==Early life and career==\nOriginally from [[Tampa, Florida]], Adderley moved to [[New York City|New York]] in 1955.<ref name=ALLMUSIC>{{cite web |last=Yanow |first=Scott |url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=cannonball-adderley-mn0000548338|pure_url=yes}} |title=Cannonball Adderley \u2013 Music Biography, Credits and Discography |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=July 8, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Cannonball-Adderley.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cannonball-adderley.com/bio.htm |title=The Cannonball Adderley Biography |website=Cannonball-adderley.com |date=September 15, 1928 |accessdate=July 21, 2017}}</ref> His nickname derived from \"cannibal\", a title imposed on him by high school colleagues as a tribute to his voracious appetite.<ref>{{cite web |author=Gilles Miton |url=http://www.cannonball-adderley.com/288.htm |title=Cannonball Adderley |publisher=Cannonball-adderley.com |accessdate=April 9, 2012}}</ref>\n\nCannonball moved to [[Tallahassee, Florida|Tallahassee]], when his parents obtained teaching positions at [[Florida A&M University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jazz.com/encyclopedia/adderley-nat-nathaniel |title=Adderley, Nat (Nathaniel)|work=Encyclopedia of Jazz Musicians|publisher=Jazz.com |date= |accessdate=December 13, 2012}}</ref> Both Cannonball and brother Nat played with [[Ray Charles]] when Charles lived in Tallahassee during the early 1940s.<ref>Lydon, Michael, ''Ray Charles: Man and Music'', Routledge (1996); updated edition, January 22, 2004, {{ISBN|0-415-97043-1}}.</ref> Adderley moved to Broward County, Florida, in 1948 after finishing his music studies at Florida A&M and became the band director at [[Dillard High School]] in [[Fort Lauderdale, Florida|Fort Lauderdale]], a position which he held until 1950.<ref name=\"Cannonball-Adderley.com\" /> Cannonball was a local legend in Southeast Florida until he moved to New York City in 1955. hi\n\nOne of his known addresses in New York was in the neighborhood of [[Corona, Queens]].<ref name=\"ALLMUSIC\" /><ref>Berman, Eleanor. [http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/06001/629777.stm \"The jazz of Queens encompasses music royalty\"], ''[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]'', January 1, 2006. Accessed October 1, 2009. \"When the trolley tour proceeds, Mr. Knight points out the nearby Dorie Miller Houses, a co-op apartment complex in Corona where Clark Terry and Cannonball and Nat Adderley lived and where saxophonist [[Jimmy Heath]] still resides.\"</ref> He left Florida originally to seek graduate studies at New York conservatories, but one night in 1955 he brought his saxophone with him to the [[Caf\u00e9 Bohemia]]. Asked to sit in with [[Oscar Pettiford]] in place of his band's regular saxophonist, who was late for the gig. The \"buzz\" on the New York jazz scene after Adderley's performance announced him as the heir to the mantle of [[Charlie Parker]].<ref name=\"Cannonball-Adderley.com\" />\n\nAdderley formed his own group with his brother Nat after signing onto the Savoy jazz label in 1957.  He was noticed by [[Miles Davis]], and it was because of his blues-rooted alto saxophone that Davis asked him to play with his group.<ref name = \"ALLMUSIC\"/> He joined the [[Miles Davis Quintet|Davis band]] in October 1957, three months prior to the return of [[John Coltrane]] to the group. Some of Davis's finest trumpet work can be found on Adderley's first solo album ''[[Somethin' Else (Cannonball Adderley album)|Somethin' Else]]'' (also featuring [[Art Blakey]] and [[Hank Jones]]), which was recorded shortly after the two giants met. Adderley then played on the seminal Davis records ''[[Milestones (Miles Davis album)|Milestones]]'' and ''[[Kind of Blue]]''.  This period also overlapped with pianist [[Bill Evans]]' time with the sextet, an association that led to recording ''[[Portrait of Cannonball]]'' and ''[[Know What I Mean?]]''.<ref name=\"ALLMUSIC\" />\n\nHis interest as an educator carried over to his recordings. In 1961, Cannonball narrated ''The Child's Introduction to Jazz'', released on [[Riverside Records]].<ref name=\"ALLMUSIC\" /> In 1962, Cannonball married actress [[Olga James]].<ref name=\"obit\" />\n\n==Band leader==\nThe Cannonball Adderley Quintet featured Cannonball on alto sax and his brother [[Nat Adderley]] on [[cornet]]. Cannonball's first quintet was not very successful;<ref name=\"Milkowski\">Milkowski, Bill, [http://jazztimes.com/articles/29295-junior-mance-saved-by-a-cannonball \"Junior Mance: Saved By A Cannonball\"], ''JazzTimes'', January 16, 2012.</ref> however, after leaving Davis' group, he formed another group again with his brother.\n\nThe new quintet, which later became the Cannonball Adderley Sextet, and Cannonball's other combos and groups, included such noted musicians as saxophonists [[Charles Lloyd (jazz musician)|Charles Lloyd]] and [[Yusef Lateef]], pianists [[Bobby Timmons]], [[Barry Harris]], [[Victor Feldman]], [[Joe Zawinul]], [[Hal Galper]], [[Michael Wolff (musician)|Michael Wolff]], and [[George Duke]], bassists [[Ray Brown (musician)|Ray Brown]], [[Samuel Jones (musician)|Sam Jones]], [[Walter Booker]], and [[Victor Gaskin]], and drummers [[Louis Hayes]] and [[Roy McCurdy]].\n\n==Later life==\n[[File:Cannonball1961 (crop).jpg|thumb|Nat and Cannonball Adderley in [[Amsterdam]], 1961]]\n\nBy the end of the 1960s, Adderley's playing began to reflect the influence of electric jazz. In this period, he released albums such as ''[[Accent on Africa]]'' (1968) and ''[[The Price You Got to Pay to Be Free]]'' (1970). In that same year, his quintet appeared at the [[Monterey Jazz Festival]] in [[California]], and a brief scene of that performance was featured in the 1971 psychological thriller ''[[Play Misty for Me]]'', starring [[Clint Eastwood]]. In 1975 he also appeared in an acting role alongside [[Jos\u00e9 Feliciano]] and [[David Carradine]] in the episode \"Battle Hymn\" in the third season of the TV series ''[[Kung Fu (TV series)|Kung Fu]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0011645/ |title=Julian \"Cannonball\" Adderley|publisher=IMDb.com|accessdate=December 13, 2012}}</ref>\n\nSongs made famous by Adderley and his bands include \"This Here\" (written by Bobby Timmons), \"The Jive Samba\", \"Work Song\" (written by Nat Adderley), \"[[Mercy, Mercy, Mercy]]\" (written by Joe Zawinul) and \"Walk Tall\"  (written by Zawinul, Marrow, and Rein). A cover version of [[Pops Staples]]' \"Why (Am I Treated So Bad)?\" also entered the charts. His instrumental \"Sack o' Woe\" was arranged by [[Herbie Mann]] on their debut album.\n\nAdderley suffered a stroke from a [[cerebral hemorrhage]] and four weeks later, on August 8, 1975, died at St. Mary Mercy Medical Center in [[Gary, Indiana]]. He was 46 years old.<ref name=obit>{{cite news |author= |agency=[[Associated Press]] |title=Cannonball Adderley, Jazzman, Dead Gary Post-Tribune, Aug 10, 1975, p. E1|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9A04E2DE1E3AE034BC4153DFBE66838E669EDE= |quote= |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=August 8, 1975 |accessdate=April 4, 2016 }}</ref> He was survived by his wife Olga James Adderley, parents Julian C. and Jessie L. Adderley, and brother Nat Adderley.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Brown|first=Geoffrey F.|date=August 28, 1975|title=The Cannonball Rests, But Brother Nat Carried On|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XrEDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA61&dq=olga+james+jet&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjB56K-4ufnAhU9l3IEHZ_PCPcQ6AEwAHoECAAQAg#v=onepage&q=olga%20james%20jet&f=false|journal=Jet|volume=|pages=58-61|via=}}</ref> He was buried in the Southside Cemetery, [[Tallahassee]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=9eEPAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA420&lpg=PA420|title=The Tombstone Tourist: Musicians|first=Scott|last=Stanton|date=September 1, 2003|publisher=Simon and Schuster|accessdate=August 1, 2018|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nLater that year he was inducted into the ''Down Beat'' [[Down Beat|Jazz Hall of Fame]].<ref name=\"ALLMUSIC\" /> Joe Zawinul's composition \"Cannon Ball\" on Weather Report's ''[[Black Market (Weather Report album)|Black Market]]'' album is a tribute to his former leader.<ref name=\"ALLMUSIC\" /> [[Pepper Adams]] and [[George Mraz]] dedicated the composition \"Julian\" on the 1975 Pepper Adams album of the same name days after Cannonball's death.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pepperadams.com/Compositions/compList/Julian/index.html#anchor |title=PepperAdams.com |publisher=PepperAdams.com |date= |accessdate=December 13, 2012}}</ref>\n\nAdderley was initiated as an honorary member of [[Phi Mu Alpha Sinfonia]] fraternity (Gamma Theta chapter, [[University of North Texas]], '60, & Xi Omega chapter, [[Frostburg State University]], '70) and [[Alpha Phi Alpha]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.apa1906.net/websites/alphaphialpha/images/notable_alphas.pdf |title=Notable Alphas |publisher=[[Alpha Phi Alpha]] |date=|accessdate=August 1, 2018 |page=11}}</ref> (Beta Nu chapter, [[Florida A&M University]]).\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Cannonball Adderley discography}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n*{{Find a Grave|8400}}\n*[http://www.cannonball-adderley.com/ The Cannonball Adderley Rendez-vous]\n*[http://www.jazzdisco.org/adderley/ Cannonball Adderley Discography at Jazzdisco.org]\n*{{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p5981|label=Cannonball Adderley}}\n*[https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=15404098 Cannonball Adderley at NPR Music]\n*{{imdb name|0011645}}\n\n{{Cannonball Adderley}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Adderley, Julian Cannonball}}\n[[Category:African-American jazz musicians]]\n[[Category:African-American woodwind musicians]]\n[[Category:American jazz bandleaders]]\n[[Category:American jazz alto saxophonists]]\n[[Category:American male saxophonists]]\n[[Category:Hard bop saxophonists]]\n[[Category:Jazz alto saxophonists]]\n[[Category:Jazz record producers]]\n[[Category:Soul-jazz saxophonists]]\n[[Category:1928 births]]\n[[Category:1975 deaths]]\n[[Category:Miles Davis Quintet members]]\n[[Category:Capitol Records artists]]\n[[Category:EmArcy Records artists]]\n[[Category:Blue Note Records artists]]\n[[Category:Savoy Records artists]]\n[[Category:Riverside Records artists]]\n[[Category:Landmark Records artists]]\n[[Category:Fantasy Records artists]]\n[[Category:Milestone Records artists]]\n[[Category:Verve Records artists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American musicians]]\n[[Category:United States Army Band musicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century saxophonists]]\n[[Category:Male jazz musicians]]\n[[Category:Cannonball Adderley Quintet members]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{short description|American jazz alto saxophonist}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Cannonball Adderley\n| image            = Julian and Nat Adderley 1966.JPG\n| caption          = Cannonball (left) with brother [[Nat Adderley]] in 1966\n| background       = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_name       = Julian Edwin Adderley\n| alias            = \n| birth_date       = {{birth date|1928|9|15|mf=y}}\n| birth_place      = [[Tampa]], [[Florida]], U.S.\n| death_date       = {{death date and age|1975|8|8|1928|9|15|mf=y}}\n| death_place      = [[Gary, Indiana]], U.S.\n| instrument       = [[Alto saxophone]], [[soprano saxophone]]\n| genre            = [[Hard bop]], [[soul jazz]], [[modal jazz]], [[Jazz fusion|jazz rock]]<ref>{{cite web |last=Ginell |first=Richard S |url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=black-messiah-mw0000870617|pure_url=yes}} |title=Black Messiah \u2013 Cannonball Adderley : Songs, Reviews, Credits, Awards |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=July 8, 2012}}</ref>\n| occupation       = Teacher, saxophonist\n| years_active     = 1955&ndash;1975\n| label            = [[Blue Note Records|Blue Note]], [[Fantasy Records|Fantasy]], [[Capitol Records|Capitol]], [[Prestige Records|Prestige]], [[Riverside Records|Riverside]]\n| associated_acts  = [[Nat Adderley]], [[Miles Davis]], [[George Duke]], [[Yusef Lateef]], [[Samuel Jones (musician)|Sam Jones]], [[Joe Zawinul]], [[Louis Hayes]], [[Bobby Timmons]], [[Bill Evans]]\n| website          = \n}}\n\n'''Julian Edwin''' \"'''Cannonball'''\" '''Adderley''' (September 15, 1928 \u2013 August 8, 1975) was an American [[jazz]] [[Alto saxophone|alto saxophonist]] of the [[hard bop]] era of the 1950s and 1960s.<ref name=obit/><ref name=\"Harvard Bio\">{{cite book |last=Randel |first=Don Michael |title=The Harvard Biographical Dictionary of Music |year=1996 |publisher=Harvard University Press |location=Cambridge, Massachusetts |isbn=0-674-37299-9 |page=[https://archive.org/details/harvardbiographi00rand/page/5 5] |chapter=Adderley, Cannonball |url=https://archive.org/details/harvardbiographi00rand/page/5 }}</ref><ref name=\"RCJE\">{{Cite book | author = Richard Cook | year = 2005 | title = Richard Cook's Jazz Encyclopedia | publisher = Penguin Books  | isbn = 0-141-00646-3 | page = 3}}</ref>\n\nAdderley is remembered for his 1966  soul jazz single \"[[Mercy, Mercy, Mercy]]\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/song/mercy-mercy-mercy-mt0009193426|title=Mercy, Mercy, Mercy \u2013 Cannonball Adderley \u2013 Song Info \u2013 AllMusic|website=AllMusic|accessdate=August 1, 2018}}</ref> a crossover hit on the pop charts (it was also covered by [[the Buckinghams]]). He worked with trumpeter [[Miles Davis]], on his own 1958 ''[[Somethin' Else (Cannonball Adderley album)|Somethin' Else]]'' album, and on the seminal Davis records ''[[Milestones (Miles Davis album)|Milestones]]'' (1958) and ''[[Kind of Blue]]'' (1959).  He was the elder brother of jazz [[trumpet]]er [[Nat Adderley]], a longtime member of his band.<ref name=\"ALLMUSIC\" />\n\n==Early life and career==\nOriginally from [[Tampa, Florida]], Adderley moved to [[New York City|New York]] in 1955.<ref name=ALLMUSIC>{{cite web |last=Yanow |first=Scott |url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=cannonball-adderley-mn0000548338|pure_url=yes}} |title=Cannonball Adderley \u2013 Music Biography, Credits and Discography |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=July 8, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Cannonball-Adderley.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cannonball-adderley.com/bio.htm |title=The Cannonball Adderley Biography |website=Cannonball-adderley.com |date=September 15, 1928 |accessdate=July 21, 2017}}</ref> His nickname derived from \"cannibal\", a title imposed on him by high school colleagues as a tribute to his voracious appetite.<ref>{{cite web |author=Gilles Miton |url=http://www.cannonball-adderley.com/288.htm |title=Cannonball Adderley |publisher=Cannonball-adderley.com |accessdate=April 9, 2012}}</ref>\n\nCannonball moved to [[Tallahassee, Florida|Tallahassee]], when his parents obtained teaching positions at [[Florida A&M University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jazz.com/encyclopedia/adderley-nat-nathaniel |title=Adderley, Nat (Nathaniel)|work=Encyclopedia of Jazz Musicians|publisher=Jazz.com |date= |accessdate=December 13, 2012}}</ref> Both Cannonball and brother Nat played with [[Ray Charles]] when Charles lived in Tallahassee during the early 1940s.<ref>Lydon, Michael, ''Ray Charles: Man and Music'', Routledge (1996); updated edition, January 22, 2004, {{ISBN|0-415-97043-1}}.</ref> Adderley moved to Broward County, Florida, in 1948 after finishing his music studies at Florida A&M and became the band director at [[Dillard High School]] in [[Fort Lauderdale, Florida|Fort Lauderdale]], a position which he held until 1950.<ref name=\"Cannonball-Adderley.com\" /> Cannonball was a local legend in Southeast Florida until he moved to New York City in 1955.\n\nOne of his known addresses in New York was in the neighborhood of [[Corona, Queens]].<ref name=\"ALLMUSIC\" /><ref>Berman, Eleanor. [http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/06001/629777.stm \"The jazz of Queens encompasses music royalty\"], ''[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]'', January 1, 2006. Accessed October 1, 2009. \"When the trolley tour proceeds, Mr. Knight points out the nearby Dorie Miller Houses, a co-op apartment complex in Corona where Clark Terry and Cannonball and Nat Adderley lived and where saxophonist [[Jimmy Heath]] still resides.\"</ref> He left Florida originally to seek graduate studies at New York conservatories, but one night in 1955 he brought his saxophone with him to the [[Caf\u00e9 Bohemia]]. Asked to sit in with [[Oscar Pettiford]] in place of his band's regular saxophonist, who was late for the gig. The \"buzz\" on the New York jazz scene after Adderley's performance announced him as the heir to the mantle of [[Charlie Parker]].<ref name=\"Cannonball-Adderley.com\" />\n\nAdderley formed his own group with his brother Nat after signing onto the Savoy jazz label in 1957.  He was noticed by [[Miles Davis]], and it was because of his blues-rooted alto saxophone that Davis asked him to play with his group.<ref name = \"ALLMUSIC\"/> He joined the [[Miles Davis Quintet|Davis band]] in October 1957, three months prior to the return of [[John Coltrane]] to the group. Some of Davis's finest trumpet work can be found on Adderley's first solo album ''[[Somethin' Else (Cannonball Adderley album)|Somethin' Else]]'' (also featuring [[Art Blakey]] and [[Hank Jones]]), which was recorded shortly after the two giants met. Adderley then played on the seminal Davis records ''[[Milestones (Miles Davis album)|Milestones]]'' and ''[[Kind of Blue]]''.  This period also overlapped with pianist [[Bill Evans]]' time with the sextet, an association that led to recording ''[[Portrait of Cannonball]]'' and ''[[Know What I Mean?]]''.<ref name=\"ALLMUSIC\" />\n\nHis interest as an educator carried over to his recordings. In 1961, Cannonball narrated ''The Child's Introduction to Jazz'', released on [[Riverside Records]].<ref name=\"ALLMUSIC\" /> In 1962, Cannonball married actress [[Olga James]].<ref name=\"obit\" />\n\n==Band leader==\nThe Cannonball Adderley Quintet featured Cannonball on alto sax and his brother [[Nat Adderley]] on [[cornet]]. Cannonball's first quintet was not very successful;<ref name=\"Milkowski\">Milkowski, Bill, [http://jazztimes.com/articles/29295-junior-mance-saved-by-a-cannonball \"Junior Mance: Saved By A Cannonball\"], ''JazzTimes'', January 16, 2012.</ref> however, after leaving Davis' group, he formed another group again with his brother.\n\nThe new quintet, which later became the Cannonball Adderley Sextet, and Cannonball's other combos and groups, included such noted musicians as saxophonists [[Charles Lloyd (jazz musician)|Charles Lloyd]] and [[Yusef Lateef]], pianists [[Bobby Timmons]], [[Barry Harris]], [[Victor Feldman]], [[Joe Zawinul]], [[Hal Galper]], [[Michael Wolff (musician)|Michael Wolff]], and [[George Duke]], bassists [[Ray Brown (musician)|Ray Brown]], [[Samuel Jones (musician)|Sam Jones]], [[Walter Booker]], and [[Victor Gaskin]], and drummers [[Louis Hayes]] and [[Roy McCurdy]].\n\n==Later life==\n[[File:Cannonball1961 (crop).jpg|thumb|Nat and Cannonball Adderley in [[Amsterdam]], 1961]]\n\nBy the end of the 1960s, Adderley's playing began to reflect the influence of electric jazz. In this period, he released albums such as ''[[Accent on Africa]]'' (1968) and ''[[The Price You Got to Pay to Be Free]]'' (1970). In that same year, his quintet appeared at the [[Monterey Jazz Festival]] in [[California]], and a brief scene of that performance was featured in the 1971 psychological thriller ''[[Play Misty for Me]]'', starring [[Clint Eastwood]]. In 1975 he also appeared in an acting role alongside [[Jos\u00e9 Feliciano]] and [[David Carradine]] in the episode \"Battle Hymn\" in the third season of the TV series ''[[Kung Fu (TV series)|Kung Fu]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0011645/ |title=Julian \"Cannonball\" Adderley|publisher=IMDb.com|accessdate=December 13, 2012}}</ref>\n\nSongs made famous by Adderley and his bands include \"This Here\" (written by Bobby Timmons), \"The Jive Samba\", \"Work Song\" (written by Nat Adderley), \"[[Mercy, Mercy, Mercy]]\" (written by Joe Zawinul) and \"Walk Tall\"  (written by Zawinul, Marrow, and Rein). A cover version of [[Pops Staples]]' \"Why (Am I Treated So Bad)?\" also entered the charts. His instrumental \"Sack o' Woe\" was arranged by [[Herbie Mann]] on their debut album.\n\nAdderley suffered a stroke from a [[cerebral hemorrhage]] and four weeks later, on August 8, 1975, died at St. Mary Mercy Medical Center in [[Gary, Indiana]]. He was 46 years old.<ref name=obit>{{cite news |author= |agency=[[Associated Press]] |title=Cannonball Adderley, Jazzman, Dead Gary Post-Tribune, Aug 10, 1975, p. E1|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9A04E2DE1E3AE034BC4153DFBE66838E669EDE= |quote= |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=August 8, 1975 |accessdate=April 4, 2016 }}</ref> He was survived by his wife Olga James Adderley, parents Julian C. and Jessie L. Adderley, and brother Nat Adderley.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Brown|first=Geoffrey F.|date=August 28, 1975|title=The Cannonball Rests, But Brother Nat Carried On|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XrEDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA61&dq=olga+james+jet&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjB56K-4ufnAhU9l3IEHZ_PCPcQ6AEwAHoECAAQAg#v=onepage&q=olga%20james%20jet&f=false|journal=Jet|volume=|pages=58-61|via=}}</ref> He was buried in the Southside Cemetery, [[Tallahassee]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=9eEPAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA420&lpg=PA420|title=The Tombstone Tourist: Musicians|first=Scott|last=Stanton|date=September 1, 2003|publisher=Simon and Schuster|accessdate=August 1, 2018|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nLater that year he was inducted into the ''Down Beat'' [[Down Beat|Jazz Hall of Fame]].<ref name=\"ALLMUSIC\" /> Joe Zawinul's composition \"Cannon Ball\" on Weather Report's ''[[Black Market (Weather Report album)|Black Market]]'' album is a tribute to his former leader.<ref name=\"ALLMUSIC\" /> [[Pepper Adams]] and [[George Mraz]] dedicated the composition \"Julian\" on the 1975 Pepper Adams album of the same name days after Cannonball's death.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pepperadams.com/Compositions/compList/Julian/index.html#anchor |title=PepperAdams.com |publisher=PepperAdams.com |date= |accessdate=December 13, 2012}}</ref>\n\nAdderley was initiated as an honorary member of [[Phi Mu Alpha Sinfonia]] fraternity (Gamma Theta chapter, [[University of North Texas]], '60, & Xi Omega chapter, [[Frostburg State University]], '70) and [[Alpha Phi Alpha]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.apa1906.net/websites/alphaphialpha/images/notable_alphas.pdf |title=Notable Alphas |publisher=[[Alpha Phi Alpha]] |date=|accessdate=August 1, 2018 |page=11}}</ref> (Beta Nu chapter, [[Florida A&M University]]).\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Cannonball Adderley discography}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n*{{Find a Grave|8400}}\n*[http://www.cannonball-adderley.com/ The Can